Wait — the `throw` case: `async doWork(): Promise<never>` where the body throws. This has no `await`, so `require-await` will fire again. Since the method throws synchronously, I can't add `await Promise.resolve()` before the throw in a meaningful way... but I can:

```typescript
async doWork(): Promise<never> {
    await Promise.resolve();
    throw boom;
}
```

But that changes the test's behavior slightly — the throw happens asynchronously (on next tick). Let me check what the test expects... it does `await expect(svc.doWork()).rejects.toThrow(...)` which will still work even if the throw happens asynchronously within the async function. Let me apply that fix:

